Analysis of the transfers to the US also show >150 substances that have matching domestic waste management options in various years, many of which constitute transfers for disposal and are thus potentially outside the Basel exceptions for recycling. Despite bilateral agreements for the handling of these hazardous wastes, which may include measures to handle these transfers in an environmentally sound manner, these examples may illuminate further opportunities to align with Canada's Basel ambitions of keeping waste close to the source if/when environmentally sound management options exist domestically (see 
                           Figs. SI–2
                        ).

Additional new perspectives on transboundary pollutant movements and the environmental performance of the Basel Convention can be gleaned by looking more specifically at the Canadian domestic rules that implement the Basel Convention: the Cross-border Movement of Hazardous Waste and Hazardous Recyclable Material Regulations (Cross-border Movement of Hazardous Waste) (established under the Canadian Environmental Protection Act) (Government of Canada, 2023b; Canadian Environmental Protection Act, 1999) also known as “XBR”. These describe a federal documentation process to track domestic interprovincial and international movements of pollutants in waste/recyclables and are a means to ensure wastes reach their intended destination and are disposed of/recycled in an environmentally sound manner (and thus risks of chemical release to the environment is reduced). The XBR require information to be reported to the Canadian government about the quantity and classification of waste moving across borders, its intended destination facility, intended disposal/recycling operations (i.e., authorized methods that minimize environmental releases), and confirmation that these intentions were achieved, though (in contrast to the NPRI) this information is not then published. This topic was included in this case study because though the XBR tracks hazardous waste by classification, tracking by specific pollutant is not done (see Methods section), whereas the NPRI can provide more granular views (in terms of specific substances, and quantities) of the movements of some (but not all, see Methods section and 
                           Tables SI–1
                        ) XBR substances in waste, thus it can provide meaningful and publicly accessible measures of SDG 12 progress in the context of chemicals management.

For example, the NPRI perspective allows a quantitative view not knowable by the SDG 12.4 official indicator, showing that in the period of 2013–2022, over 340,000 t of ‘hazardous waste or hazardous recycling material’ (i.e. the NPRI data associated with 91 XBR-relevant substances, see 
                           Tables SI–1
                        ) were moved out of Canada to over 600 facilities in 19 countries (all Basel-compliant, as discussed above; see Figs. SI–3). As mentioned above, these transboundary movements appear to be driven mainly by transfers for recycling (90%), and comprised mainly zinc, copper and lead going abroad for recovery of metals and metal compounds to nations as close as the US (∼300,000 t) and as far away as Australia, Sri Lanka, Japan, and Europe. By contrast, international transfers for either disposal or treatment were less common (∼20,000 t and ∼13,000 t, respectively) and went mainly to the US, with the exception of the two international disposals discussed above. Importantly, the 2013–2022 trend in the total quantities of XBR-relevant substances (i.e., the subset of XBR substances tracked by the NPRI, 
                           Tables SI–1
                        ) being transferred by NPRI facilities out of Canada is increasing (+4%), driven by copper, lead, and manganese recycling, whereas the number of facilities generating these quantities is decreasing (∼164–137), meaning fewer NPRI facilities are generating and moving more cross-border hazardous waste. The median and range of quantities transferred per substance are shown in Fig. 3
                         and are each relatively small (median 1.2 t, range <0.01 t to >5000 t), though these occur frequently enough to add up substantially over time. This view using NPRI data shows that regardless of effective documentation on the cross-border movement of these substances (and thus contributing to Canada's Basel Convention information submission obligations), their totals are increasing, which diverges from the downward trends expected by Basel Convention's aim of “minimization of generation and international movement of hazardous waste”, and the downwards trends in chemical wastes expected by SDG 12.
